## Technical Specifications

- Data Models
  - Cronjob
    - id: string
    - name: string
    - enabled: boolean
    - scheduleExpression: string | null
    - scheduleUI: object | null (builder state)
    - timezone: string
    - triggerType: 'time' | 'event' | 'conditional'
    - targetType: 'agent' | 'workflow'
    - targetId: string
    - inputPayloadTemplate: string
    - permissionsLevel: 'viewer' | 'editor' | 'admin'
    - automationLevel: 'suggest-only' | 'approval-required' | 'auto-execute' | 'bounded-autopilot'
    - constraints: {
      maxActions?: number
      spendLimit?: number
      allowedTools?: string[]
    }
    - safetyRails: string[] (required confirmations)
    - retryPolicy: {
      maxRetries: number
      backoffMs: number
      deadLetterTarget?: string
    }
    - outputsConfig: {
      artifacts?: string[]
      logs?: boolean
      traceEnabled?: boolean
    }
    - ownerId: string
    - module: string
    - tags: string[]
    - createdAt: string
    - updatedAt: string
    - lastRun?: { status: string; startedAt: string; finishedAt: string; durationMs: number }
    - nextRun?: string
  - CronjobRun
    - runId: string
    - cronjobId: string
    - status: 'success' | 'failure' | 'skipped' | 'running'
    - startedAt: string
    - finishedAt: string
    - durationMs: number
    - artifacts: any[]
    - logs: string[]
    - trace: any

- API Endpoints
  - GET /api/cronjobs?filters&page&pageSize&sort
  - POST /api/cronjobs
  - GET /api/cronjobs/:id
  - PUT /api/cronjobs/:id
  - PATCH /api/cronjobs/:id
  - DELETE /api/cronjobs/:id
  - POST /api/cronjobs/:id/run-now
  - POST /api/cronjobs/bulk
  - GET /api/cronjobs/:id/runs
  - GET /api/cronjobs/alerts
  - GET /api/master-dashboard/summary
  - GET /api/performance/health

- Security
  - JWT/OAuth-based authentication; role-based access control (RBAC) with module-level scoping
  - Validation on server: input schema validation, strict type checks, and restrictions on dangerous operations
  - Audit trails for create/update/delete/run actions
  - Data minimization and encryption for sensitive payloads

- Validation
  - Client: input fields validated with inline messages; schedule builder validates cron expressions in real-time
  - Server: robust validation with explicit error messages; use schema validation (e.g., Zod/Joi) to ensure shapes

- Validation Rules (Runtime Safety)
  - Supabase-like data guards: data ?? [] when reading lists
  - Always guard array operations: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : []
  - Initialize state with correct types: useState< Cronjob[] >([]) and useState<string>("") for strings, etc.
  - API response shapes: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
  - Optional chaining: apiObj?.field?.nested
  - Destructuring with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

- Performance & Optimization
  - Caching: client-side memoization; server-side query caching for cronjob lists
  - Indexing: database indices on name, ownerId, module, tags, nextRun
  - Monitoring: lightweight telemetry for schedule latency, run durations, error rates
  - Debounce and pagination to keep UI responsive as data grows

---

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] The Cronjobs Dashboard renders a safe, fully interactive list/grid with correct guards for all array data (no runtime crashes from null/undefined).
- [ ] All array operations use null-safe patterns (data ?? [], Array.isArray checks) and use correct useState defaults for arrays.
- [ ] Schedule Builder supports presets and cron-expression input with live next-run previews and timezone handling.
- [ ] Quick Create and Cronjob Editor validate inputs in real time and persist correctly to backend with proper server-side validation.
- [ ] Bulk actions perform atomic operations with proper confirmations and reflect updated state in the UI.
- [ ] Run history panels display per-cronjob runs with correct status, timing, and artifacts; all data access guarded against nulls.
- [ ] Master Dashboard integration surfaces global search, alerts, and quick-access workflows with consistent styling.
- [ ] Performance panel reports on caching/indexing/monitoring health with non-blocking UI behavior.
- [ ] All API endpoints are protected by RBAC and validated; responses match expected shapes and include safe defaults.

---

## UI/UX Guidelines

Apply LifeOps design system rigorously:

- Color Palette and Theme
  - Follow the provided dark, high-contrast palette with restrained accents
  - Use accent red sparingly for critical actions or alerts
  - Employ teal, amber, and purple selectively for data viz/status
- Typography and Layout
  - Inter or similar geometric sans; consistent weight hierarchy
  - Dense but legible information density with 8px baseline rhythm
  - Thicker section titles and card headers; body text is legible in 12–14px range
- Card and Surface
  - Dark elevated cards with 8–12px radii
  - Subtle inner glows and top-edge highlights
  - Hover/focus lift with depth changes
- Navigation
  - Left collapsible/expandable navigation with active state indicator
  - Breadcrumb and top bar for context; consistent alignment
- Data Visualization
  - Minimalistic charts with muted gridlines; emphasized series with the accent colors
  - Tooltips and legends in dark panels with rounded corners
- UI Interactions
  - Smooth transitions 120–200ms
  - Clear affordances for actions; confirm destructive operations
  - Accessible controls with focus indicators and ARIA attributes

---

## Visual Style (Recap)

- Branding and components follow the specified color palette, typography, spacing, and depth rules
- Cards, navigation, and data visuals reflect a cohesive, developer-focused aesthetic
- All interactive elements employ subtle but clear affordances and states

---

## Mandatory Coding Standards — Runtime Safety (enforced)

- Supabase/DB-like results always default to non-null arrays:
  - const items = data ?? []
- Array method safety:
  - (items ?? []).map(...)
  - Array.isArray(items) ? items.filter(...) : []
- React useState defaults for arrays:
  - const [cronjobs, setCronjobs] = useState<Cronjob[]>([])
- API response shapes:
  - const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : []
- Optional chaining:
  - obj?.field?.nested
- Destructuring with defaults:
  - const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}

